## 5. Database Implementation

### 5.1 Prisma Schema for Phase 1

Create a new schema file or modify existing one:

```prisma
// prisma/schema.prisma - Phase 1

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

model Task {
  id          String     @id @default(uuid()) @db.Uuid
  title       String     @db.VarChar(200)
  description String?    @db.Text
  status      TaskStatus @default(PENDING)
  createdAt   DateTime   @default(now()) @map("created_at")
  updatedAt   DateTime   @updatedAt @map("updated_at")

  @@map("tasks")
  @@index([status])
  @@index([createdAt])
}

enum TaskStatus {
  PENDING     @map("pending")
  IN_PROGRESS @map("in_progress")
  COMPLETED   @map("completed")
}

// Note: User model and relations will be added in Phase 2
```

### 5.2 Migration Strategy

```bash
# Step 1: Backup existing migration if any
# Step 2: Reset migrations for clean Phase 1 start (if starting fresh)
npx prisma migrate reset --force  # WARNING: Destructive in production!

# Step 3: Create Phase 1 migration
npx prisma migrate dev --name init_phase1_tasks

# Step 4: Generate Prisma client
npx prisma generate
```

### 5.3 Index Optimization

The schema includes these indexes:
- `status` - For filtering tasks by status (frequent query pattern)
- `createdAt` - For default sort order (newest first)

Additional considerations for Phase 3:
- Compound index `(userId, status)` for user-specific status queries
- Compound index `(userId, createdAt)` for user task pagination

